{"key":"post-12498189","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12498189</id>\n<content>Listen guys.&amp;nbsp; The micropore tape over the holes works to prevent contamination from entering the jars/verm filter &lt;b&gt;before&lt;/b&gt; you inoculate.&amp;nbsp; Otherwise, contaminant spores can be on top of the verm, and your needle can push them through to the inside.&amp;nbsp; That's the only reason to use it.&amp;nbsp; It's not needed but is an added insurance policy.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After inoculation, you can leave the wound in the tape exposed.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A verm filter will work unless you jerk with your jars too much and disturb it.&amp;nbsp; The vermiculite filter must be left alone to work.&amp;nbsp; If you turn the jars upside down back and forth a few times, you stir those contaminant spores down into your substrate.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12499553</next>\n<prev>12496793</prev>\n<first>12491300</first>\n<last>12499553</last>\n<when>1272903518</when>\n<utime>05/03/10 07:18 PM</utime>\n</post>"}